Sorry for the delay.

I have tested this patch locally by referencing a .target file packaged into a jar using a jar-URL and it worked for a single location that only contains the eclispe.sdk, but it failed for a more complex target file with multiple locations that contain multiple elements.

In the complex example the resolution of the locations failed, which only became clear because the child targets show zero available targets. The IUBundleContainer seems to not report errors that occured during resolution, because the fResolutionStatus is reset to OK in the beginning of AbstractBundleContainer.resolve() but the actual synchronization usually happened already and therefore overrides failures. But I'm not yet sure why this failure happen.

Furthermore I think we need a dedicated ExternalTargetHandle that is also handled in TargetPlatformService.getTarget(String memento). The reason is that during resolution in P2TargetUtils.synchronize() a P2-Profile is created/registered using the target-handles memento. When the Workspace is saved on shutdown, orphans are removed from the P2-Profile-Registry and in that process the memnto is restored to a TargetHandle. But currently this does not work for external non-file targets.
The question is if the ExternalFileTargetHandle should be replaced or if a separate ExternalTargetHandle class should be created.

When creating the test cases I also tried to consider corner-cases like
1. a launch-config that was created and saved when only one version of a bundle was available and therefore no version was written, but later another version of that bundle was added (to the workspace or the TP)
2. a plug-in/bundle in the workspace and a bundle in the TP but both have different versions. When building in the workspace PDE does not consider target-bundles if a corresponding plug-in with same Bundle-symbolic-name is present in the workspace (I assume it is because they are then not considered 'active'). Nevertheless it can be required to add both version (from the workspace and the TP) to a launched Eclipse-App if e.g. another plug-in in the TP requires that particular version from the TP.

Therefore I think a bundle selected in the target platform should be included even if a similar workspace plug-in is present.

What do you think about it?

Patch Set 1:

> I'm surprised about the automatic re-flow on windows as the eclipse terminal keeps its own line wrapping information. Will have a look at it on a windows box.

I am normally on Linux, but I have been doing a bunch of work on Terminal for Windows recently. The implementation of the PTY there is massively different because the shell does not "talk" to Eclipse directly, but via an intermediary (ConPTY or WinPTY) and that intermediary does the reflowing, not the CDT code. So when the window is resized, ConPTY sends a clear screen and resends everything.

In other words, it may not be worth comparing the Windows one too much.
